## About Me

My name is David Sanson.
I'm a professor of philosophy here at Illinois State.
I regularly teach courses in logic, metaphysics, epistemology, 
 medieval philosophy, medieval Islamic philosophy, and philosophy of language.
But I'm also interested in social and political philosophy, feminist philosophy,
 philosophy of race, philosophy of sport, philosophy of games, 
 aesthetics and philosophy of art, philosophy of mind, ancient Greek philosophy, 
 and early modern philosophy, 
 among other things.

I've published research on puzzles about the nature of time and change,
 the nature of possibility and necessity, 
 the status of nonexistent objects the
 ontology of fictional characters,
 the history of the Liar Paradox,
 and the relationship between a thing and its parts.
At the moment, I am writing a book with a friend
 on the history of the Liar Paradox in the Islamic world.

I mention all of this because you are a student at a *University*.
Part of what that is *supposed* to mean is that
 you have a chance to engage intellectually with *professors* 
 who aren't just *teachers* but *researchers*,
 and spend their time working on and thinking about cool things.
I enjoy talking about all sorts of philosophical problems and puzzles.
You are always welcome to drop by my office hours just to talk.
It's part of what I am here for, 
 and it is part of what you are here for.

That doesn't just apply to me. 
You should make an effort to talk to all of your professors!

```{.QualitativeProblem .ShortAnswer give-credit="onSubmission" points=10}
2 Are there any "philosophical" problems that you've thought about? What are they?
```

:::{.reaction .correct ex=2}
Open-ended questions like these 
 are meant to give you a moment to stop and reflect on what you've just read. 
You get credit for writing *something*.
I can *see* your answers,
 and I'd be happy to talk with you about them.
But unless you ask, I am unlikely to look at your answers,
 and I will not provide any feedback.
:::

