## Course Description

This is a class in formal logic. 

Logic is the study of correct and incorrect reasoning. 
Logicians want to understand what makes good reasoning good and bad reasoning bad.
This helps us avoid making mistakes in our own reasoning, and it allows us to evaluate the reasoning of others. 
There are several ways we might go about studying correct and incorrect reasoning.
Formal logic proceeds by studying logical form, 
 and thinking about how logical form contributes to making good reasoning and bad reasoning bad.

Studying formal logic will deepen your understanding of the structure of information,
 and deepen your understanding of the ways language encodes and expresses this information.
It will give you tools for thinking more clearly and carefully about the structure of reasoning.
Because of this, formal logic lies at the foundation of several disciplines,
 including mathematics, linguistics, cognitive science, and computer science.
In mathematics, it provides a rigorous model of mathematical proof.
In linguistics, an understanding of logical form underlies the study of syntax and semantics.
In computer science, 
 formal logic underlies basic chip design,
 and provides the basic model of computation.
Computers are, basically, machines that understand formal logic.
In cognitive science,
 formal logic provides the foundations of a computational theory of the mind,
 and an important model of how reasoning might work.

Of course, formal logic is also important in philosophy. 
In philosophy, we try to think as clearly and carefully as possible
 about anything and everything worth thinking about.
Part of that is thinking as clearly and carefully as possible about the *reasons* people give
 for believing what they do.
In philosophy, we articulate reasons as arguments, consisting of premises
and a conclusion.
Formal logic is a tool for understanding and assessing these arguments.

## Course Objectives and Concerns

A complete [list of course objectives](#learning-objectives-by-unit), 
 divided into units, can be found below.
But most of those won't make much sense yet.
Instead, let me talk about my big picture objectives for you in this course,
 and some barriers to achieving those objectives.

If you are a philosophy major, this is your "formal methods in philosophy" class. 
If you are taking this to fulfill your Quantitative Reasoning (QR)
 or Science, Mathematics, and Technology (SMT) requirement,
 you can think of this as your "formal methods for thinking about anything" class. 
These aren't really different: 
 In philosophy, we try to think as clearly and carefully as possible 
 about anything and everything worth thinking about.
So that's my first course objective:
 I want you to learn formal logic,
 so you can get better at thinking as clearly and carefully as possible
 about anything and everything worth thinking about.

The course concept in this course is the concept of *validity*,
 a property of some good arguments.
An argument is valid when its conclusion *follows* from its premises,
 in a sense of 'follows' that we will define carefully.
So my one overarching *content-related* objective for you is this:
 I want you to have a working understanding of the concept of validity,
 and how to apply it to arguments.

In school, you studied arithmetic and algebra.
Those are abstract formal tools for thinking about numbers and quantities.
You also studied geometry,
 an abstract formal tool for thinking about shape and space. 
Logic is another abstract formal tool, 
 but it is for thinking about *reasoning itself*. 
So just as your algebra teacher wanted you to learn how to think more clearly and carefully about numbers and quantities,
 and your geometry teacher wanted you to learn how to think more clearly and carefully about shapes and space, 
 I want you to learn how to think more clearly and carefully about reasoning itself.

What does that even mean?
Formal tools in any domain are powerful 
 because they provide a way of thinking and calculating 
 that is different from "common sense" and informal intuition.
Someone who has mastered calculus 
 can use it to analyze complex physical interactions that baffle common sense. 
A confusing word problem may easily be solved by someone who knows how to construct an appropriate graph.
Formal logic gives us the tools needed for untangling complex bits of reasoning,
 and unexpected inferences and entailments.

Here is one barrier I worry about.
You may have an unhappy history with math.
Parts of this class will remind you of algebra,
 and that might freak you out!
But I assure you, formal logic is *much simpler* than algebra,
 and if you struggle, I will help you understand it.
It *isn't about numbers*.
It's about *language* and *information*, 
 and how we use language to express and encode information.
I've known many people who are "bad at math" or "hate math",
 but loved formal logic. 
This might be you too!

In fact, this class tends to make most students uncomfortable.
If you are good with language but bad with math,
 you may struggle with the "math-y" bits.
If you are good with math but bad with language,
 you may struggle with the "language-y" bits.
Even if you are good at both,
 you may find it hard to move back and forth between the two.
This class involves thinking about language in a math-y way,
 and thinking about math in a language-y way.
It combines ways of thinking that you are used to keeping separate.
This can be jarring,
 but it can also be powerful.

This is not a course in abstract theory.
It is a course in problem solving.
You will learning about validity by learning how to use tools for recognizing
validity.
Some of the problems will involve the application of these tools to English,
 encouraging you to think about how sentences are put together,
 and what that tells us about logical form.
Some of these problems will be puzzles,
 asking you to find a pathway---a line of reasoning---from some given
 premises,
 to a given conclusion,
 using a limited set of formal inference rules.
And some of the problems will ask you to think about
 what it takes for some given sentences to be true or false,
 and what that tells us about the logical relations between them.
In every case, you will be learning how to *do* something,
 so this class will involve a lot of exercises,
 and a lot of opportunities to learn through practice.

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points=10}
5 This class might be challenging for you because
| *it combines both mathematics and language
| it will be taught entirely in French 
| it is a course in abstract theory
```

:::{.reaction .correct ex=5}
C'est la seule partie de ce cours qui est en français.
:::

