## Course Format

This class is "flipped". 
That means I will not be lecturing.
*Before class*, I expect you to work through the reading (which include videos),
 and try to make sense of the material yourself.
*In class*, we will work together to understand anything that was confusing.

In my experience, this works much better than a traditional lecture course.
But it doesn't always *feel so great*.
[Research suggests](https://www.pnas.org/node/889733) 
 that students *feel like they learn more* from a good lecture,
 but actually learn less.
This course is designed to maximize your actual learning,
 by giving you the chance to do enough on your own to get confused,
 and giving us the time together, in class, to work through that confusion.

At times, it may feel like I am asking too much:
 like I am expecting you to figure everything out on your own.
But that's not it at all!
I am expecting you to *try* to figure it out on your own,
 but I am not expecting you to *succeed* all on your own.
I am 100% here to help.
Since I am not lecturing,
 I can devote 100% of my time and attention to helping.

But I can't help you if you don't come to class!
I mention this because every term,
 I have some students who reach a point where they get stuck,
 and so they get frustrated,
 and feel defeated.
And class doesn't offer a lecture,
 with its comforting illusion of understanding.
So instead of coming to class,
 and asking for help,
 they cocoon and feel isolated,
 and just stop, and fall behind.

Don't fall into this trap!
If you are stuck and frustrated, that's good!
It means this class isn't too easy for you!
Make sure, when this happens, to *come to class*,
 and be *proud* about the fact that you are completely fucking confused!
This course is *designed* for this!
We *can work through* that confusion,
 and you *will* understand it.

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleSelection points=10}
7 This course won't have lectures because (select all correct answers):
| the professor is lazy and doesn't want to teach
| the professor thinks the material is easy and everyone should be able to understand it without his help
| the professor doesn't know how to lecture
| *the professor believes that lecturing is not the most effective way to actually teach logic
8 If I find myself confused, frustrated, and discouraged in this class (select all correct answers):
| I should probably just give up because I am not smart enough to learn logic
| I should be embarrased because I am not studenting correctly
| *I should be proud of the fact that I am trying to figure out something that is hard
| *I should come to class and ask for help
| I should isolate myself in a cocoon of despair
```

## Assignment Structure

This class uses a *mastery grading scheme*. In a traditional grading scheme, you
march through all the material at a set pace, whether you understand it or
not. In a mastery grading scheme, the pace is flexible, and you are expected
to *complete* each unit, showing that you understand the material, before
moving on to the next. Your grade for the course is based upon how many units
you complete.

The class is divided into 19 units of content (plus two "bonus" collaboration
units).
Each unit is divided into three parts:

-   **Reading**, which includes embedded videos and interactive questions;
-   **Exercises**, based on the material covered in the reading;
-   A **Mastery check**, based on the reading and exercises;

You complete a unit by completing all three parts. If you do especially well
on the mastery check, we say that you have not just *completed* the unit, but
*mastered* the unit.

:::xed
   Course Grade                        Requirement
  -------------- -----------------------------------------------------------------------
        A         at least 18 units completed, at least 12 of which are also mastered
        B         at least 16 units completed, at least 10 of which are also mastered
        C         at least 14 units completed
        D         at least 10 units completed
:::

Revised 3/3/22:

   Course Grade                        Requirement
  -------------- -----------------------------------------------------------------------
        A         at least 16 units completed, at least 10 of which are also mastered
        B         at least 14 units completed, at least 8 of which are also mastered
        C         at least 12 units completed
        D         at least 8 units completed

I may adjust these standards to be more generous if needed.

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points=10}
9 To complete a unit,
| one must complete the mastery check; everything else is optional
| *one must complete the reading, exercises, and mastery check
| one must attempt the reading, exercises, and mastery check
10 To get an B in this course,
| one must complete 26 units (16 complete + 10 mastered)
| *one must complete 16 units (and at least 10 of those 16 must also be mastered)
| one must score a B or higher on the final exam
11 True or false: this course has a final exam
| True
| *False
12 If I complete the reading and exercises for every unit, but fail to complete any of the mastery checks,
| my grade in the course will probably be a C or a D, since I did a lot of work
| *my grade in the course will be an F, even though I did a lot of work
| my grade in the course will depend on how many total points I earned on the readings and exercises
```

## Completing and Mastering

To [complete]{.vocab} a unit, you must complete all three parts: reading,
exercises, and mastery check. Each part has a different standard for what
counts as "complete". Here is the standard for "completing" a unit:

-   Reading = 100%
-   Exercises ≥ 80%
-   Mastery check ≥ 60% 

As mentioned above, if you do especially well on the mastery check, we say
that you have not just completed the unit, but *mastered* it. The standard for
"especially well" is scoring at least 80%. So here is the standard for
"mastering" a unit:

-   Reading = 100%
-   Exercises ≥ 80%
-   Mastery check ≥ 80%

## Reading

To complete the Reading, you need to score 100%.
Reading questions are scattered through the reading. 
They are designed to get you to stop and think about what you've just read,
 or stop and try out something that has just been introduced.
It is not possible to submit wrong answers.
If you try to submit an answer that is wrong,
 you will be told that it is wrong,
 and asked to try again.
Where needed, solutions are provided,
 in case you cannot figure the solution yourself,

## Exercises

To complete the Exercises, you need to score 80%.
Exercise questions are based on what you learned in the reading,
 and are meant to give you a chance to practice what you have learned.
As with the reading questions, it is not possible to submit wrong answers.
But solutions are not provided,
 so you must figure out the solutions by yourself.

## Mastery Checks

Mastery Checks are short low-stakes open-book exams.
The questions are the same in kind as those in the exercises.
But on a mastery check, it *is possible* to submit wrong answers.
So the training wheels have been removed.

To complete a mastery check, you need to score at least 60%.
And to do "especially well", you need to score at least 80%.
So, if a mastery check has 3 questions,
 you need to get 2 out of 3 to complete it,
 and 3 out of 3 to do especially well.

Mastery Checks are low-stakes because **you can retake them as many times as
needed**. So, if you would like to improve your score, request a retake, by
sending me a DM on Discord. If you score lower on a retake, don't worry: I
will count your highest score.

Although you can retake a mastery check as many times as needed, 
 you are only allowed to request **two retakes a week**. 
If you don't do well on a mastery check,
 you should request a retake.
But first, you should figure out what went wrong.
Otherwise, you are likely to do just as poorly on the retake.
One great way to figure out what went wrong is to talk with me about it!

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points=10}
13 To complete a reading assignment,
| *I must answer all the questions correctly
| I must answer most of the questions correctly, but not all
14 To complete an exercises assignment,
| *I must score at least 80%.
| I must score at least 60%.
| I must answer all the questions correctly.
15 I can retake a mastery check
| once, if I request a retake within a week of the due date
| twice, but I only have a week to do so
| *as many times as needed, but I only get to request two retakes a week
16 If I fail a mastery check,
| I should retake it, and hope that I do better
| *I should figure out what went wrong, so I won't make the same mistake again, and then retake it
| I should give up on that unit, and move on to the next
```

## The Collaboration Units

There are two bonus "collaboration units".
These are meant to recognize and motivate your engagement in the class,
 and your collaboration with your peers.
Learning logic is easier when you are part of a community of logic learners!

Genuine engagement and collaboration are hard to measure.
Attempts to quantify such things often lead to annoyance and insincerity.
Think of schemes that require "one discussion board post"
 and "one comment on somebody else's discussion board post":
 in your experience, is that likely to generate genuine discussion?
In my experience, it motivates folks to do the bare minimum,
 and the result is underwhelming.

So I will make no attempt to measure genuine engagement and collaboration.
But if you come to class, I will make every effort to encourage it.
Hopefully, we can come together into a friendly and supportive community,
 and help each other learn logic.

To help make that possible, 
 I will award 10 "collaboration points" for each class meeting you attend,
 whether in person or on Zoom. 
If you earn at least 100 collaboration points, 
 that counts as "completing" one collaboration unit.
If you earn at least 200 collaboration points,
 that counts as "completing" *two* collaboration units.
These units are added to your tally of completed units,
 and so can easily bump a D to a C, or a C to a B, or a B to an A.

Note that collaboration units can be "completed", but they cannot be "mastered".

I am aware that we are still in the middle of a global pandemic, and the last
thing I want to do is encourage you to attend class when doing so is not safe.
Note that these standards make it possible to complete both collaboration
units despite missing several classes for reasons outside your control.

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points=10}
17 Collaboration points are awarded for attendance because (select all correct answers)
| the professor believes that attendance is the same thing as genuine collaboration and engagement
| *the professor believes that attempts to measure genuine collaboration and engagement usually don't work out very well
| *the professor believes wishes to encourage attendance, in hopes of fostering a friendly and supportive community in the classroom, which supports collaboration and engagement
```

## Due Dates

Because this course uses a mastery grading scheme, 
 it is designed to be flexible when it comes to deadlines.
The whole point of a mastery grading scheme is that,
 if you need more time to complete a unit,
 you should take that time,
 and learn the material,
 rather than rushing on to the next thing.

Each assignment has a due date.
This due date is displayed on your Carnap user page.
It is highly recommended that you *attempt* to complete each assignment by this date.
That will keep you on track to do well in the course.
It will often be possible for you to complete assignments well before the due date.
This is also highly recommended: 
 it will give you a cushion, 
 allowing you to stay on track when later units prove challenging,
 and require more time.

There is no penalty for turning in assignments late.
Behind the scenes,
 Carnap gives problems turns in late half points.
But my grading scheme doesn't pay attention to this,
 and will still give you full credit for late work.

The final due date for all submissions is Friday of Finals Week, at 5pm.

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points=10}
18 Late work
| will be penalized
| *will not be penalized
19 The final due date for all submissions is
| the last day of finals week, at midnight
| *the last day of finals week, at 5pm
| the last day of class, by the end of the class period
```

